e rise of the philosophy known as <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Absurdism\" title=\"Absurdism\">absurdism<\/a>. He wrote in his essay \"<a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/The_Rebel_(book)\" title=\"The Rebel (book)\">The Rebel<\/a>\" that his whole life was devoted to opposing the philosophy of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nihilism\" title=\"Nihilism\">nihilism<\/a> while still delving deeply into individual freedom.<\/p><p>Camus did not consider himself to be an <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Existentialist\" title=\"Existentialist\" class=\"mw-redirect\">existentialist<\/a> despite usually being classified as one, even during his own lifetime.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Albert_Camus#cite_note-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> In an interview in 1945, Camus rejected any ideological associations: \"No, I am not an existentialist. <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Jean-Paul_Sartre\" title=\"Jean-Paul Sartre\">Sartre<\/a> and I are always surprised to see our names linked...\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Albert_Camus#cite_note-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Camus was born in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Algeria\" title=\"Algeria\">Algeria<\/a><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Albert_Camus#cite_note-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Albert_Camus#cite_note-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Albert_Camus#cite_note-5\"><span>[<\/span>5<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> to a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Pied-Noir\" title=\"Pied-Noir\">Pied-Noir<\/a> family, and studied at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Algiers\" title=\"University of Algiers\">University of Algiers<\/a>. In 1949, Camus founded the Group for International Liaisons within the Revolutionary Union Movement after his split with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Garry_Davis\" title=\"Garry Davis\">Garry Davis<\/a>'s Citizens of the World movement.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Albert_Camus#cite_note-6\"><span>[<\/span>6<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> The formation of this group, according to Camus, was intended to \"denounce two ideologies found in both the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Soviet_Union\" title=\"Soviet Union\">USSR<\/a> and the USA\" regarding their idolatry of technology.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Albert_Camus#cite_note-7\"><span>[<\/span>7<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Camus was awarded the 1957 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_for_Literature\" title=\"Nobel Prize for Literature\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Nobel Prize for Literature<\/a> \"for his important literary production, which with clear-sighted earnestness illuminates the problems of the human conscience in our times\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Albert_Camus#cite_note-8\"><span>[<\/span>8<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"Albert Camus","place_of_birth":"Mondovi , Algeria","place_of_death":"Villeblevin , France","text":"Albert Camus ,  born in French Algeria , Literature, 1957","year":1957.0}